 diseases using C. elegans as a model. I used Autocad to design the microscale apparatuses personally, and I designed an algorithm capable of precisely timing bright LED flashes to stimulate C.elegans worms optogenetically. I utilized COMSOL simulations to create detailed simulations to predict with high confidence the electronic and fluidic properties of the models. I then enhanced the program to automate the experimental setup experiment process and standardize the results.\nDarryl then worked as a Signal Processing Scientist at Abbvie, where he led an effort to design a novel algorithm to diagnose and categorize Parkinson’s Disease in patients from the comfort of their homes using wearable Inertial measurement units (IMU) such as Apple Watches or ActiGraph. I utilized machine learning to predict with high confidence the progression of patient disease and worked with Clinical Research Coordinators and Principal Investigators to effectively obtain and analyze clinical trial data. I led weekly presentations discussing my findings with his department to further Parkinson’s treatment.\nCurrently, \nLumere is a startup with the ambitious goal of changing the way our healthcare system delivers medical care through access to unbiased clinical evidence and actionable analytics to make better decisions.\n\nMy role:\n I provided subject matter expertise to evaluate various FDA-approved medical devices to provide doctors, nurses, and health system executives with life-saving data for them to make the best purchasing decisions. He uses medical product spending data provided by partners to provide evidence-based savings strategies and spend utilization insights. Darryl interacts directly with customers to ensure their happiness by listening and understanding exactly what their problem is to best address it. He collects product-specific data from the FDA, peer-reviewed journals, and device manufacturers to allow clients to fully understand product functionality and adverse even